deck: Powerful member of the Protectorate.
description:
Origin

Technocrat is a technology based superhero and member of the Protectorate, a powerful group of superheroes. Alongside the other members of the Protectorate White Bird, Thor, Nightfighter, Citydweller, Nicola Zeitgeist, Technocrat would help protect the Earth, having frequently saved the Earth and reality itself multiple times. The Protectorate exist to protect, when things need protection. They operate out of a subspace location known as the Foldcastle which grants them to be anywhere they need at a moments notice.

Creation

Technocrat is a Marvel comics published character created by Steven Grant, Warren Ellis and Ariel Olivetti. Technocrat first appears in the X-Man series in the issue X-Man #71 - Fearful Symmetries Part 1. Technocrat is an analogue/homage to the Authority team's Engineer character.

Major Story Arcs

The Burning Tiger Qabiri

Technocrat and the Protectorate encounter the mysterious inter-dimensional interloper Qabiri of the Shining City. Qabiri had set New York ablaze killing all its seven million citizens. Citydweller, Nightfighter, White Bird and Technocrat would be first to confront Qabiri, but their attempts to subdue him would fail, Qabiri manhandling the quartet with his power. Respite would come as Thor, Zeitgeist and Nate Xavier would arrive, the power of the team. Qabiri would leave suddenly, confusing the Protectorate, but Thor and the Professor would follow him.

Powers and Abilities

Technocrat utilizes advanced technology and nano machines to various effect.
name: Technocrat

deck: Powerful psychic and member of the Protectorate.
description:
Origin

Nate Xavier, also known as the Professor and Professor X was a member of the powerful Protectorate, a group of superheroes that have frequently saved the Earth and reality itself multiple times. Nate Xavier is considered one of the more powerful members of the group, alongside Zeitgeist and Thor, with Nate Xavier the psychic and telepathic member of the team and also capable of inter-dimensional travel. The rest of their numbers include the powerhouse Thor, the flying warrior White Bird, the technology affiliated Technocrat, the computer enhanced Nightfighter and Citydweller who has an affinity and connection to cities, and Zeitgeist, the spirit of the century. The Protectorate exist to protect, when things need protection. They operate out of a subspace location known as the Foldcastle which grants them to be anywhere they need at a moments notice. Nate Xavier and The Protectorate's home reality is Earth - 253. Nate Xavier and the rest of his team eventually come into conflict with a man known as Qabiri, and call on aid from X-Man, Nate Grey and his companion at the time Sister Perpetua.

Creation

Nate Xavier is a Marvel comics published character created by Steven Grant, Warren Ellis and Ariel Olivetti. Nate Xavier first appears in the X-Man series, specifically issue X-Man #71 - Fearful Symmetries Part 1. The Professor aka Nate Xavier is a member of the Protectorate, that team also created by Steven Grant, Warren Ellis and Ariel Olivetti. The Protectorate bare an uncanny resemblance to Wildstorm comics Authority team and book, with each member being a parallel of an Authority team character. Given that Warren Ellis created many of both and was involved in both teams creations, the parallels aren't as unoriginal as one could accuse the characters of being. Nate Xavier specifically is an analogue/parallel to the Authority's Doctor.

Character Evolution

Nate Xavier appears to not only be a nod to the Authority character the Doctor, but carries the names Nate and Xavier, giving the character connections to both Nate Grey, the character whose book Nate Xavier first appears and Professor Charles Xavier. Incidentally Nate Xavier is also a powerful telepathic character.

Major Story Arcs

The Burning Tiger Qabiri

Nate Xavier and his team Protectorate encounter the mysterious inter-dimensional interloper Qabiri of the Shining City. Qabiri had set New York ablaze killing all its seven million citizens. Citydweller, Nightfighter, White Bird and Technocrat would be first to confront Qabiri, but their attempts to subdue him would fail, Qabiri manhandling the quartet with his power. Respite would come as Thor, Zeitgeist and Nate Xavier would arrive, after finishing a mission in another dimension. Qabiri would leave suddenly, confusing the Protectorate, but Thor and the Professor would follow him. The duo would be forced to fight against Qabiri, with Thor's stubborn and direct physical attack getting him killed.

Powers and Abilities

Nate Xavier possesses powerful psychic abilities.
name: Nate Xavier

deck: Citydweller can speak to and communicate with cities. Also a member of the Protectorate.
description:
Origin

Citydweller is a superhero and member of the Protectorate. Citydweller, also known as Jerry, appears human, however has a radically different physiology, almost as if composed of concrete, mortar, steel and electricity. Citydweller is inherently linked to cities and relies on their own existence for his own. This symbiotic relationship with large urban structures allows Citydweller to experience cities as if they were sentient individuals with their own personalities and mannerisms, and allows for communication between Citydweller and various cities as well as grants him powers and abilities within cities.

A member of the Protectorate, he serves alongside Zeitgeist, Professor (Nate Xavier), Thor, White Bird, Nightfighter and Technocrat. Their team has been successful for many years in safeguarding their world and reality, existing to protect, when things need protection. They operate out of a subspace location known as the Foldcastle which grants them to be anywhere they need at a moments notice.

Creation

Citydweller is a Marvel comics published character created by Steven Grant, Warren Ellis and Ariel Olivetti. The character first appears in the X-Man series, near the latter end of the series, appearing for the first time in the issue X-Man #71 - Fearful Symmetries Part 1. He appears alongside his team as a group introduction. Citydweller as well as the rest of his team bare somewhat obvious similarities with Wildstorms Authority team and members.

Analogues of the characters exist as follows. Nightfighter and Midnighter, Thor to Apollo, Professor X and the Doctor, White Bird to Swift, Technocrat to the Engineer, Nicola Zeitgeist and Jenny Sparks. Lastly with Citydweller as an analogue of Jack Hawksmoor.

Character Evolution

Citydweller appears as supporting character in the latter end of the X-Man series. Introduced alongside a new team of superheroes the character only appeared for a limited number of issues and is unlikely to appear again. The character is also notable as far as being a member of a team directly inspired by the Authority. Whilst characters like Superman, Batman, Spiderman and teams like Justice League and Avengers and Fantastic Four are often used as a source for imitation, the Authority being a much newer and modern team has fewer examples.

Major Story Arcs

The Burning Tiger Qabiri

Citydweller was the first member of the Protectorate to become aware of an alien visitor to their world Qabiri. Qabiri had attracted attention in New York city of Earth 253 by hovering above it and observing the people below him. After a time Qabiri would then unleash a fire attack that would kill all the cities people. The Protectorate would be too late to save them entering from out of their Foldcastle. Qabiri would be more than a match for the powerful team, when the more powerful members of the team Thor, Zeitgeist and Professor would show up Qabiri would fly away prompting Thor and Professor to follow. Citydweller was the first to have his health negatively affected by Qabiri as he holds an empathetic bond with cities, Manhattan was dead, Queens was catatonic, Brooklyn sobbed and the Bronx had flashed Citydweller a rude gesture. Citydweller's health reliant on cities he had began to suffer, losing his eyesight and weakening physically. Qabiri would go on to destroy various cities such Reykjavik, Osaka, Santiago, Nairobi, and D.C. and this level of city destruction would have a crippling effect on Citydweller. Technocrat who Citydweller harbored feelings for would also be fatally wounded, Citydweller confession feelings for her he would eventually die frozen partially crumbled after Qabiri's destruction of most of Earths cities. Qabiri would go on to kill the rest of the Protectorate except for Zeitgeist.

Powers and Abilities

Citydweller possesses a unique and powerful physiology, resembling a human but with a symbiotic connection to man made city structures. Citydweller relies on city structures for his health, his distance from urban structures weakening him, his close proximity to them empowering him. Citydweller can interact and communicate with cities as if they were human, and he can gain super powered levels of strength, durability, agility, speed, resilience and size with their aid. Citydweller can essentially become a part of any given city and as such requires no conventional nutrition or sustenance. Citydweller can teleport using cities or garner information from them.

Citydweller can also control parts of city in his immediate proximity. Injury to or destruction of cities will however have a negative toll on Citydweller.
name: Citydweller

deck: Powerful heavy hitter of the Protectorate.
description:
Origin

Thor is a member of the Protectorate, a powerful group of superheroes that have frequently saved the Earth and reality itself multiple times. Thor is considered one of the more powerful members of the group, alongside Zeitgeist and the Professor, and Thor is also considered the most powerful physical member. The rest of their numbers include flying warrior White Bird, the technology affiliated Technocrat, the computer enhanced Nightfighter and Citydweller who has an affinity and connection to cities. The Protectorate exist to protect, when things need protection. They operate out of a subspace location known as the Foldcastle which grants them to be anywhere they need at a moments notice.

Creation

Thor is a Marvel comics published character created by Steven Grant, Warren Ellis and Ariel Olivetti. Thor first appears in the X-Man series in the issue X-Man series, specifically issue X-Man #71 - Fearful Symmetries Part 1. Thor is a member of the Protectorate, that team also created by Steven Grant, Warren Ellis and Ariel Olivetti. The Peoples Protectorate bare an uncanny resemblance to Wildstorm comics Authority team and book, with each member being a parallel of an Authority team character. Given that Warren Ellis created many of both and was involved in both teams creations, the parallels aren't as unoriginal as one could accuse the characters of being.

The analogues of character exist as follows. Nightfighter and Midnighter, Thor to Apollo, Professor X and the Doctor, White Bird to Swift, Citydweller and Jack Hawksmoor, Technocrat to the Engineer, Nicola Zeitgeist and Jenny Sparks.

Character Evolution

This pages Thor despite sharing a name with Marvel's most popular and biggest thunder god and Asgardian Thor, seemingly has no connection or relationship with the Stan Lee and Jack Kirby adapted character. There are similarities as far as both characters possessing super strength, flight abilities, fabulous long flowing hair and being the powerhouse of their respect teams, but this version of Thor actually pays homage and is an analogue of Apollo, Apollo incidentally a homage to DC's premier superhero Superman.

Major Story Arcs

The Burning Tiger Qabiri

Thor and his team Protectorate encounter the mysterious inter-dimensional interloper Qabiri of the Shining City. Qabiri had set New York ablaze killing all its seven million citizens. Citydweller, Nightfighter, White Bird and Technocrat would be first to confront Qabiri, but their attempts to subdue him would fail, Qabiri manhandling the quartet with his power. Respite would come as Thor, Zeitgeist and Nate Xavier would arrive, the power of the team. Qabiri would leave suddenly, confusing the Protectorate, but Thor and the Professor would follow him.

Powers and Abilities

Thor possesses incredible physical strength and power, the power of flight, and flight at supersonic speeds, incredible durability and resistance to physical injury. Thor is resistant to extreme heat and harsh cold. Thor can fly in and withstand the vacuum of space. Thor is extremely fast. There is a limit to Thor's power however as demonstrated when the uber powerful Qabiri kills the powerhouse with his energy forcefield.
name: Thor

deck: Member of the Protectorate, Nightfighter uses supercomputers integrated with his nervous system.
description:
Origin

Nightfighter is a crime fighter, superhero and member of the Protectorate, a powerful group of superheroes, that are named after their goal of protecting things that need to be protected and being self appointed protectors of Earth and reality. He serves alongside the other members of the Protectorate White Bird, Thor, Citydweller, Nicola Zeitgeist, Technocrat. They have frequently saved the Earth and reality itself multiple times from multiple threats, including alien invasions, ending world hunger and fixing time itself. They operate out of a subspace location known as the Foldcastle which grants them to be anywhere they need at a moments notice.

Nightfighter's cerebral cortex and nervous system has been replaced by an interlocking chain of microscopic computers that allows for a variety of effects, such as running through various possible outcomes in any given situation and allowing him to predict outcomes.

Creation

Nightfighter is a Marvel comics published character created by Steven Grant, Warren Ellis and Ariel Olivetti. Technocrat first appears in the X-Man series in the issue X-Man #72 - Fearful Symmetries Part 2. Nightfighter is an analogue/homage to the Authority team's Midnighter character. The Midnighter character himself a combination of influences from Batman, the Shadow, with some influence from John Woo. Nightfighter also has some traits similar to Captain America.

Character Evolution

Nightfighter is a supporting character in the latter quarter of the X-Man series.

Major Story Arcs

The Burning Tiger Qabiri

Nightfighter the Protectorate encounter the mysterious inter-dimensional interloper Qabiri of the Shining City. Qabiri had set New York ablaze killing all its seven million citizens. Citydweller, Nightfighter, White Bird and Technocrat would be first to confront Qabiri, but their attempts to subdue him would fail, Qabiri manhandling the quartet with his power. Respite would come as Thor, Zeitgeist and Nate Xavier would arrive, the power of the team. Qabiri would leave suddenly, confusing the Protectorate, but Thor and the Professor would follow him.

Powers and Abilities

Nightfighter can predict possible outcomes and use his above human physical capabilities to exploit gaps as predicted and anticipated.
name: Nightfighter

deck: Member of the Protectorate, and possesses large white wings.
description:
Origin

White Bird lives on Earth 253 and is a superhero and a member of the powerful superhero team the Protectorate. Her first name Amara, White Bird is distinguished by her large and beautiful swan like angel wings which grow from her back, allowing her flight and extra maneuverability. She serves alongside the physical powerhouse Thor, the cyborg like technological expert the Technocrat, the telepathic and telekinetic world walker The Professor (Nate Xavier), the computer enhanced methodical Nightfighter, the city dependent and powered Citydweller and finally the spirit of the century Nicola Zeitgeist. There team operates out of the Foldcastle, an advanced high tech base, and they frequently save and protect the world from various threats, including alien invasions, ending world hunger and rebuilding time.

Creation

White Bird is a Marvel comics published character created by writers Steven Grant, Warren Ellis and artist Ariel Olivetti. The character White Bird first appears in the X-Man series, near the end of the series, appearing for the first time in the issue X-Man #71 - Fearful Symmetries Part 1 released in 2001.

Character Evolution

White Bird exists primarily as a supporting character in the first volume of the X-Man series.

Major Story Arcs

The Burning Tiger Qabiri

White Bird and the Protectorate confront an alien visitor to their world after he attacks and burns New York City killing all its inhabitants. The Protectorate would be too late to save them exiting from their Foldcastle headquarters they would get straight to stopping Qabiri. White Bird would be hurt severely and require medical attention with Technocrat assisting her and Nightfighter back to the Foldcastle. Zeitgeist and Professor would show up Qabiri would fly away prompting Thor and Professor to follow.

Powers and Abilities

White Bird possesses a unique and powerful physiology, resembling a human but with large giant white wings protruding from her back. She can fly with these massive appendages and at extremely fast speeds as well. She is also generally enhanced with increased strength, durability, agility, resiliency, speed, reflexes and healing abilities.
name: White Bird

deck: One of the Seven Dieties of Asura's Wrath, Yasha is Asura's brother-in-law who blames him for his sisters death.
description:
Powers and Abilities:

As one of the elite demi-god fighters of the Seven Deities and a former member of the Eight Guardian Generals, Yasha is immortal and possesses vast superhuman strength, speed, durability, dexterity and endurance that is on par with Asuras in his first three forms.

Due to his extensive training as a soldier, a martial artist and a member of the Eight Guardian Generals, Yasha is an exceptional warrior and has mastered many styles of hand-to-hand combat. His extraordinary fighting ability makes him one of the finest combatants in the Demigod Fleet on par with Asura in terms of physical combat skills. The source of his incredible power is based on his ability to manipulate Mantra, the source of mystic ability in the universe. It can be drawn from the elements, planets, stars, and especially peoples life force. For Yasha, his primary emotion source for amplifying his Mantra is melancholy.

In addition to these abilities, one of Yasha's greatest attributes is his incredible superhuman speed which he especially emphasizes in combat, allowing him to run significant distances within mere seconds and move within the blink of eye. He also has immense superhuman strength, stamina and durability, as he was able to remain active in various arduous situations even after battles with powerful opponents such as Deus, The Gohma Vlitra, and even Chakravartin, and still have enough strength to fight Asura before his second death. Even before Asura's supposed betrayal, Yasha was his equal in raw power and fighting ability which was not only the reason for their rivalry, but also for their close friendship.

Yasha also possesses a unique ability where he can form blue energy blades which can slice through anything, even the hardened body of the demonic Gohma, the primary adversaries of the Eight Immortal Generals. Yasha also uses an energy enhanced kick which has the raw power to smash through every known material. Like Asura, he can also use enhanced lightining punches of immense power to defeat his enemies.
name: Yasha

deck: A CIA and Secret service operative, Helena Harper is one of the main characters in Resident Evil 6.
description:
Origin

Helena Harper is an United States Secret Service Agent, a former CIA (Central Intelligence Agency) agent, and formerly of the United States military. Although highly competent and skilled in many aspects of her career, she has also had a history of incidents regarding her impulsiveness and tendency to use excess force when dealing with suspects and criminals. In two specific situations, one which involved a murderer taunting relatives of the victim, and the other involving Helena's sister being the victim of domestic abuse, both would lead to Helena using physical violence against the two perpetrators. It would be these incidents that would also catch the attention of Derek C. Simmons, a member of the government, as the National Security Advisor. He would manipulate Helena by using her sister, leading her to sabotage the security of the President of the United States, Adam Benford for whom she was supposed to be safeguarding. This was not something she did lightly, but at Ivy University in Tall Oaks, where the President was visiting, Simmons plan was executed, and the President and many others were exposed to biological weapons, essentially turning them into zombies. Amidst the chaos, Helena's consciousness would flair and she would attempt to prevent the disaster. However only former Raccoon Police Department officer and current Secret Service Operative Leon Kennedy would believe her plea and offer to assist her.

The two would have to fight off a zombie outbreak as they headed to a church to find more information. They would discover that Neo Umbrella and Simmons were the main catalysts behind the attack. They would be aided in their efforts by Ada Wong, as Simmons had framed them, leaving their normal resources unavailable to them. They would also come across Agent Sherry Birkin and Jake Muller, who they would assist as well as be assisted by. The two would also come across Chris Redfield and his new partner Piers Morgan. Despite some initial tension arising on account of conflict between the two groups over what to do with Ada, both teams would eventually help each others efforts in stopping Simmons and his newly created zombie apocalypse.

Creation

Helena Harper is a fictional character created by Capcom. She appears in various mediums and media, primary around the Resident Evil 6 storyline.

Powers and Abilities

Helena Harper is a trained and competent Secret Service member. Formerly a CIA agent as well as having military experience. She has firearm training as well as unarmed training.

Physical Characteristics

  • Height: 5'7"
  • Weight: 120 lbs
  • Eyes: Brown
  • Hair: Brown
name: Helena Harper
